752 90.1349C247.331 89.3099 246.741 88.4568 246.577 87.7542C246.418 87.0689 246.61 86.298 247.26 85.4981C248.595 83.8564 251.644 82.4143 255.519 82.3403C259.341 82.2673 263.848 83.537 267.983 87.1465C272.121 90.7589 275.941 96.7633 278.279 106.239L280.221 105.76C277.809 95.9863 273.816 89.5834 269.298 85.6398C264.777 81.6934 259.784 80.2584 255.481 80.3407C251.231 80.4219 247.53 81.9949 245.708 84.2367C244.78 85.3786 244.293 86.7666 244.63 88.2084C244.962 89.6329 246.044 90.8751 247.748 91.8645L248.752 90.1349Z"></path><defs><clippath id="clip0_376_1006"><rect transform="matrix(0.992092 0.12551 -0.126103 0.992017 12.3655 0)" fill="white" height="92.1105" width="168.546"></rect></clippath></defs></svg></svg></div><button type="button" class="chakra-button css-1qfy3s1" disabled="">Run Code</button><button type="button" class="chakra-button css-5n9w05">Submit</button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><span id="__chakra_env" hidden=""></span></div><script id="__NEXT_DATA__" type="application/json">{"props":{"pageProps":{"slug":"sql-average-post-hiatus-1","runtime":"postgres","isMobile":false,"dehydratedState":{"mutations":[],"queries":[{"dehydratedAt":1774078314873,"state":{"data":{"id":32,"createdAt":"2022-07-31T15:35:46.963Z","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T17:51:18.520Z","category":"SQL","difficulty":"Easy","title":"Average Post Hiatus (Part 1)","description":"Given a table of Facebook posts, for each user who posted at least twice in 2021, write a query to find the number of days between each user’s first post of the year and last post of the year in the year 2021. Output the user and number of the days between each user's first and last post. \n\np.s. If you've read the [Ace the Data Science Interview](https://www.amazon.com/dp/0578973839?ref_=pe_3052080_397514860) and liked it, consider writing us a review?\n\n### `posts` Table:\n|Column Name|Type|\n|:----|:----|\n|user_id|integer|\n|post_id|integer|\n|post_content|text|\n|post_date|timestamp|\n\n### `posts` Example Input:\n|user_id|post_id|post_content|post_date\n|:----|:----|:----|:----|\n|151652|599415|Need a hug|07/10/2021 12:00:00|\n|661093|624356|Bed. Class 8-12. Work 12-3. Gym 3-5 or 6. Then class 6-10. Another day that's gonna fly by. I miss my girlfriend|07/29/2021 13:00:00|\n|004239|784254|Happy 4th of July!|07/04/2021 11:00:00|\n|661093|442560|Just going to cry myself to sleep after watching Marley and Me.|07/08/2021 14:00:00|\n|151652|111766|I'm so done with covid - need travelling ASAP!|07/12/2021 19:00:00|\n\n### Example Output:\n|user_id|days_between|\n|:----|:----|\n|151652|2|\n|661093|21|\n\nThe dataset you are querying against may have different input \u0026 output - **this is just an example**!\n","solutionExplanation":"First, we can use the [`MIN()` and `MAX()` aggregate functions](https://datalemur.com/sql-tutorial/sql-aggregate-functions) on the `post_date` column to retrieve the earliest and latest post dates, and substract one from another accordingly.\n\nTo calculate the difference for each user, we `GROUP` the results by `user_id`, and then filter for posts made in the year 2021. To do so, we use the [`DATE_PART()` function](https://datalemur.com/sql-tutorial/sql-date-time-function) to extract the year from the `post_date` column.\n\nIn the final step, to exclude users who have posted only once during the year, we apply the [`HAVING` clause](https://datalemur.com/sql-tutorial/sql-having) with a [`COUNT()`](https://datalemur.com/sql-tutorial/sql-aggregate-functions) condition greater than 1.\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n\tuser_id, \n    MAX(post_date::DATE) - MIN(post_date::DATE) AS days_between\nFROM posts\nWHERE DATE_PART('year', post_date::DATE) = 2021 \nGROUP BY user_id\nHAVING COUNT(post_id)\u003e1;\n```","company":"Facebook","seoDescription":"Facebook SQL Interview Question: Write a query to obtain days between users first and last post in 2021.","slug":"sql-average-post-hiatus-1","servedTables":["posts"],"properQuery":"SELECT  \tuser_id,      MAX(post_date::DATE) - MIN(post_date::DATE) AS days_between FROM posts WHERE DATE_PART('year', post_date::DATE) = 2021  GROUP BY user_id HAVING COUNT(post_id)\u003e1;","active":true,"sort":10350,"ogTitle":"Average Post Hiatus | Facebook SQL Interview Question","baseQuery":"SELECT * FROM posts;","accessGroups":null,"datasetGroupId":32,"ogImage":"https://api.datalemur.com/assets/63ddbcb4-c744-4664-81f7-6d3f0c28cee3","questionImage":"https://api.datalemur.com/assets/02b4f675-1156-4041-b3d0-246c46cc43be","companyInfo":{"id":4,"name":"Facebook","icon":"b3826fe9-1eee-4124-b395-a188f037ae1e"},"supportedRuntimes":["postgres","mysql"],"usedInBlogTutorial":false,"defaultRuntime":"postgres","hints":[{"id":"76bd2cf7-faa3-4638-bc6f-886de1b9f701","text":"Do you know how to obtain the last and first post per user?\nTry using the `MIN` and `MAX` functions, and then substract one from another.\n\nFind more info about [MAX](https://www.postgresqltutorial.com/postgresql-aggregate-functions/postgresql-max-function/) and [MIN](https://www.postgresqltutorial.com/postgresql-aggregate-functions/postgresql-min-function/) functions.","order":1,"runtimes":["postgres","mysql"],"question_id":32},{"id":"93c4361d-17b6-4eef-81ab-d5a1031c626a","text":"Here you go, fill in the the remaining columns yourself!\n\n```sql\nSELECT\n  fill_in_column,\n  MAX(post_date::DATE) - MIN(post_date::DATE)\nFROM posts\nGROUP BY \n  fill_in_column\n```\n\nDid you notice that we were asked to find the results only for the users who have posted twice during the year 2021? Let's break this down.\n\nFirst, `DATE_PART` is a useful function to extract a part of a date (e.g. day, month, year) from a given input date. Read more [here](https://www.postgresqltutorial.com/postgresql-date-functions/postgresql-date_part/)\n\nCheck the code snippet below and replace 'part' with the desired granularity.\n```sql\nDATE_PART('part', post_date)\n```\n\n*Psst, note that we can't use DATEDIFF and TIMESTAMPDIFF functions as these are MySQL's functions.*","order":2,"runtimes":["postgres"],"question_id":32},{"id":"a6156e91-60c4-45ea-8162-6de40aae4069","text":"Here you go—fill in the remaining columns yourself!\n\n```sql\nSELECT\n  fill_in_column,\n  DATEDIFF(MAX(DATE(post_date)), MIN(DATE(post_date)))\nFROM posts\nGROUP BY \n  fill_in_column;\n```\n\nDid you notice that we're only interested in users who have posted more than once during the year 2021? Let's break this down.\n\nFirst, the YEAR() function in MySQL helps extract the year from a DATE or DATETIME value. Learn more about the YEAR() function.\n\nNow go ahead and complete the query with the appropriate filters and conditions!","order":2,"runtimes":["mysql"],"question_id":32},{"id":"9ffd4f92-c30e-487c-b357-b7cad3418857","text":"Here you go—copy, paste, and try it out yourself! But I’ve left a small task for you. To focus on users who have posted more than once, you’ll need to count the number of posts and exclude users with only one post.\n\nNow think about this: should you use WHERE or HAVING for this condition?\n\nHere’s a quick reminder—WHERE filters individual rows before grouping, while HAVING filters groups after aggregation.\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n    user_id, \n    DATEDIFF(MAX(DATE(post_date)), MIN(DATE(post_date))) AS days_between\nFROM\n    posts\nWHERE\n    YEAR(post_date) = 2021\nGROUP BY \n    user_id\nCLAUSE -- Replace CLAUSE with HAVING or WHERE\n    COUNT(post_id) \u003e 1;\n```","order":3,"runtimes":["mysql"],"question_id":32},{"id":"f6e80208-8dd0-4c73-97ad-977b7b3c0aab","text":"Here you go - copy-paste it, and try it out yourself. However, I have still left a small task for you. \nTo focus on the users who have posted more than once, you can `COUNT` the number of posts and exclude users with 1 post only.  What do you think, should you use `HAVING` or `WHERE` for this?\n\nTo offer some background, `HAVING` clause applies to the group as whole, while `WHERE` applies to individual rows.\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n\tuser_id, \n    MAX(post_date::date)- MIN(post_date::date) AS days_between\nFROM\n\tposts\nWHERE\n\tDATE_PART('year',post_date::date)=2021 \nGROUP BY \n\tuser_id\nCLAUSE -- Replace CLAUSE with WHERE or HAVING\n\tCOUNT(post_id)\u003e1\n```\n\n","order":3,"runtimes":["postgres"],"question_id":32}],"companyName":"Facebook","companyIcon":"b3826fe9-1eee-4124-b395-a188f037ae1e","companyId":4},"dataUpdateCount":1,"dataUpdatedAt":1774078314790,"error":null,"errorUpdateCount":0,"errorUpdatedAt":0,"fetchFailureCount":0,"fetchFailureReason":null,"fetchMeta":null,"isInvalidated":false,"status":"success","fetchStatus":"idle"},"queryKey":["Question","sql-average-post-hiatus-1",{"runtime":"postgres"}],"queryHash":"[\"Question\",\"sql-average-post-hiatus-1\",{\"runtime\":\"postgres\"}]"},{"dehydratedAt":1774078314873,"state":{"data":{"id":"af499b2c-5fd8-476a-9997-c6f40fe3e010","firstName":"Tokshika","lastName":"Sharma","email":"tokshikas@gmail.com","password":null,"location":null,"title":null,"description":null,"tags":null,"avatar":null,"language":null,"tfaSecret":null,"status":"active","role":null,"token":null,"lastAccess":"2026-02-06T23:49:45.851Z","lastPage":null,"provider":"clerk","externalIdentifier":"user_38JXzOLU1xguBbmhbcTfQXnMBay","authData":null,"emailNotifications":true,"createdAt":"2026-01-15T23:15:55.465Z","userName":"Tokshika Sharma","emailVerified":true,"referralCode":"HTaomETX","inviterCode":null,"accessGroups":null,"customerId":null,"appearance":null,"themeDark":null,"themeLight":null,"themeLightOverrides":null,"themeDarkOverrides":null,"theme":"auto","solvedQuestionsCount":0,"utmSource":null,"utmMedium":null,"utmCampaign":null,"utmTerm":null,"utmContent":null,"continent":"NA","country":"US","allSolvedQuestionsCount":3},"dataUpdateCount":1,"dataUpdatedAt":1774078314873,"error":null,"errorUpdateCount":0,"errorUpdatedAt":0,"fetchFailureCount":0,"fetchFailureReason":null,"fetchMeta":null,"isInvalidated":false,"status":"success","fetchStatus":"idle"},"queryKey":["User"],"queryHash